Heat broiler to high. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince @garlic{2%cloves}. Dice @roma tomato{2}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, a drizzle of @olive oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a medium, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground turkey{10%oz} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a medium, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat (use a large, preferably ovenproof, pan for 4 servings). Add garlic, @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp}, and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste; cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add tomatoes and season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @tomato paste{1.5%oz}; cook, stirring, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in @water{1%cup}, @mushroom stock concentrate{1}, and @cream cheese{4%tbsp}. Bring to a simmer and cook, stirring, until fully combined. Season generously with salt and pepper.

> Use pan used for turkey here, keeping turkey in pan.

Add @cheese tortelloni{9%oz} to pan; cook, stirring, until sauce has thickened and tortelloni are tender, ~{4-6%minutes}. If sauce is too thick before tortelloni are tender, add a splash of water. Turn off heat.

Stir in @butter{2%tbsp} until melted. Season with salt and pepper. If sauce seems too thick, add a splash of water.

> If pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture now to a #baking dish{}.

Evenly sprinkle tortelloni with panko mixture. Broil until panko is golden brown, ~{2-4%minutes}. Watch carefully to avoid burning. Garnish with more chili flakes if desired.

Divide between plates and serve.